@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xii) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it defines a MULTI-CLAUSE `def`: `fib` has three clauses, two with
-- literal-pattern params (`fib(0)`, `fib(1)`) and one general. eval dispatches across the
-- clauses by trying each in order (applyFn); the lowerer emits ONE JS `function` per `def`
-- and refuses a `def` with more than one clause — the clause-dispatch (a `match` on the
-- argument tuple, in effect) is not yet compiled. The differential harness must report it
-- `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier — never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value (reified by a `Block` IIFE; see compile_matchvalue_test).
-- (String interpolation `"{x}"` and pipe `|>` were never frontiers — both desugar upstream,
-- to `++` concat and a saturated `Call` respectively, and have compiled since D1(i).) The
-- frontier now sits at MULTI-CLAUSE `def`s — clause dispatch over the argument patterns.
-- This file defines one, so it still refuses; when clause dispatch lowers (a later D1
-- slice, as a `match` on the parameter tuple), it flips from `unsupported` to a print.

def fib(0): Number
  0
def fib(1): Number
  1
def fib(n: Number): Number
  fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2)

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(fib(10))
